column1: What will be the United Arab Emirates' ranking in the Global Food Security Index for 2022, according to the Economist Intelligence Unit?
column6: ['Society', 'Economic Indicators']
I think I may have drastically misjudged this question. The 2022 puts the UAE at #23. Is the question is asking about the 2022 report or the 2023 report?
I'm confused. Are the data for resolution of this question already available?
The uae is had a strategy in place on ferdal level and local level as Dubai emirate.

UAE ranked first in the Middle East and North Africa on the Global Food Security Index (GFSI) 2022, issued by Economist Impact, compared to the third place in the region for the year 2021. Globally, the UAE reached 23rd place, marking an improvement of 12 points from the previous year.
COVID restrictions ended, learned hard lesson on food security
the UAE adopted many initiatives relevant to food security lately and provided importance and priority to this agenda during COVID.
Because of absolutely record-high food prices, with no end in sight, I'm just not as sanguine as the crowd about prospects here, despite all the efforts of the UAE on this front. I hope I am wrong.

Given increased food prices and the export ban from India it seems less likely they'll make progress again, although it also doesn't look like they'll move much from their #35 ranking in 2021. 1 in 3 odds of slipping 6 spots, especially when high oil prices are filling the bank accounts, seems unlikely, I'm thinking more like 1 in 4 or 1 in 5, so I'll split the difference and go 22%

Thinking about it again. Looking at UAE's score for 2012 (61.4), that would have put them at #42 out of 105. 113 countries are now ranked using the index, so their ranking in 2012 if all current countries were included would likely have been close to 42. 2012 saw extremely high food prices, too. So, given that they were ranked 35th in 2021, I think a fall is very likely, but perhaps not to below 55th place. Still, given the unprecedented prices and that we may not yet have seen the end of the increases, I'll leave that as a possibility.
All-time high food prices, in a country that imports much of its food. Even in a wealthy country focusing on food security, this will have an impact.
UAE appears to be solidly in the mid-30's over the past decade with minimal changes - expect that to be maintained

Adjusting my forecast even lower, as the FAO Food Price Index is really about to take off. It will almost certainly be over 150 by March or April, and it's not clear to me at all whether it will stop there. All countries will see greater food insecurity, but ones that depend more on imports will tend to have an even harder time. I think we can expect riots and social unrest, in general, triggered directly and indirectly by increasing food prices in many countries, as prices spike even higher than they have already climbed during the pandemic. I suspect it's going to be really bad in some places around the world. Hopefully the UAE can help its population through this time through its focus on food security. https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/

Food prices will soon be at their all-time high since 1961, in both real and nominal terms: https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/ I don't see how this won't have an impact on the relative food security of a country that depends greatly on imports. Last year, the UAE was at #35. It's possible that they could fall below #41 in 2022, despite their best intentions.
The Russian war in Ukraine will negatively affect UAE's position in the index.

Food is getting really, really expensive to import. Record-breaking expensive. The last time it was this high, there were worldwide demonstrations over food prices and lots of political unrest. I'm sure the UAE is doing a lot to increase food availability, but even so, high prices will have an effect. So I'm adjusting my forecast downward.
UAE had to figure out how to feed a sudden influx of low income/refugees. I bet they've stepped-up their food game in domestic farming.
Oil prices make cost less of an issue but inflation, war, and shipping make it less secure, so now expecting them higher on the ranking than initially
Because of the war in Ukraine, imports are going to get even more expensive. So, I'm tilting my forecast slightly downwards.
Go (largely) with the flow.

Between record fertilizer prices, exorbitant shipping costs, other pandemic disruptions, and now an upcoming war in Ukraine, a major breadbasket country, I don't think the last bin is likely. Last year, the UAE moved from #42 to #35, a huge step. I don't think it's likely that they'll be able to move up 11+ places this year, though. Once pandemic conditions resolve to some extent, I'm sure they can.

Did anyone notice that the rankings came out for 2021? Or is it just me that missed it until now? UAE was #35. So: 2019: #21 2020: #42 2021: #35 That makes bin 1 look very unlikely and bin 2 most likely. I anticipate global food prices to increase a great deal in 2022, though, and that will likely impact countries that depend more on imported food, like UAE, more than others. But shipping issues will hopefully at least start to resolve in 2022.

Rethinking a bit. I suspect that despite the UAE's highly laudable focus on food security, given its current relative level of dependence on imports compared to other countries, and currently increasing shipping and food prices, it might be hard for the UAE to improve its food security situation in 2022.

Rethinking. Even though this is a tough year for countries having to import much of their food, the UAE's focus on food security, together with the country's overall wealth, is likely to cause relevant organizations in the country to try hard to make progress this year given the situation. So I'm shifting my forecast to a more optimistic one.

Rethinking. Given their focus on the issue, despite the extent of their current dependence on imports, I don't think it's likely they'll fall to below 55th in rankings. I am torn about whether their attempts to improve security will dominate, or the current situation with increasing food and shipping prices.

Given the dependence of the UAE on imports and the global situation, which is causing delays and price increases, I am adjusting my forecast downward. I continue to believe that given the focus of the UAE government on this important topic, they will rise in the rankings in the years to come, as the shipping situation improves and also as their domestic agricultural development continues to advance.

Spreading my forecast out more, just in case. Rethinking a bit. As I wrote in my previous forecast, I do think they will climb back up in food security because it's a priority for them. But I think the fact that they rely so much on imports, which are shipped, will likely keep them from making much progress this year. The shipping situation seems to be even worse this year than last year, in terms of both delays and prices. In addition, the FAO Food Price Index has continued to go up in 2021, which makes improving food security even harder, although it does that everywhere to some extent. So I'm revising downwards a lot and not ruling out a fall into the first bin, which is not that far below where they were in 2020.

Major issues seem to hinge on environment and dependency on imports. The big suggestion seems to be investment in R & D, which isn't likely a short term fix although it should lead to some progress. The global supply chain issues are likely to continue into 2022 and again affect their scoring on this list, although the mid-range forecasts call for some resolution to these issues in the coming year. It seems the most likely scenario is a small improvement, but depending on the world at the time of scoring it seems possible they could regain their 2019 placement.

Now the UAE is 42nd, but it's been improving over the years. Its rank was 49 in 2012. According to a linear regression of the scores (data from 2012 to 2020, then forecasting 2021 and 2022), the UAE should be #38 in 2022 (therefore majority of probability is between 40-26, while the other possibility is that it's higher than 40. 2021 data should arrive in 02/2022.
Because ya gotta eat !
Neighboring Saudi Arabia is #1 and rising high in the ranks is a stated goal

This is a tough one because small changes translate into large difference in rankings. 31st place in 2018, 21st place in 2019, 42nd place in 2020. It depends most on what the UAE does but also on what happens in the rest of the world. The UAE has clearly placed an emphasis on increasing food security, and their efforts and results have been impressive (as in other fields as well, including Covid vaccination). As ensuring food security is among the most important functions of government, this effort will increase not only their population's well being but also regime stability and national prosperity.

Food is abundant in UAE. The continued logistics jams may hinder free flow of food, but I think food supplies are pretty secure. Also, the latest developments in foodtech and Agritech go in a positive direction for UAE.
